  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between moratorium and full underwriting?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        <strong>Moratorium (Allianz):</strong> No medical questionnaire. All pre-existing conditions automatically excluded. If you're symptom-free for 2 years, conditions may become covered. Simpler process.
        <br/><br/>
        <strong>Full underwriting (Aetna):</strong> Complete medical questionnaire required. Insurer reviews each condition and decides: cover it, exclude it, or add premium. More thorough but can result in better coverage for some conditions.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Allianz really 20-30% cheaper?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Yes, when US coverage isn't needed. The gap is real and consistent across age groups. However, once you add US coverage to Allianz, prices become similar to Aetna. The savings only apply if you skip US coverage.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How valuable is CVS integration really?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        For Americans who visit home: genuinely valuable. You can fill prescriptions at any CVS, walk into MinuteClinic for minor issues, and use a familiar pharmacy system. For non-Americans who never visit the US: no value at all.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Which has better mental health coverage?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Neither excels here. Aetna is marginally better with more consistent inclusion across plans. If mental health is a priority, BUPA Global is significantly better than both Allianz and Aetna.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I switch between them later?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Yes, but switching triggers new underwriting. Any conditions you've developed become pre-existing for the new insurer. If you're healthy, switching is straightforward. If you've had health issues, staying put is usually better.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if my employer offers Aetna?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Take it seriously. Corporate Aetna rates are typically 20-30% better than individual plans, with potentially enhanced benefits. Unless you have specific reasons to prefer Allianz (like not needing US coverage and wanting to save more), employer-sponsored Aetna is usually a good deal.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

