  <h2 id="verdict">Our Verdict</h2>

  <p>
    The Allianz vs Aetna decision usually comes down to one question: Do you need US coverage?
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Choose Allianz Care</strong> if you don't need US coverage. The 20-30% savings are real and significant over years. Allianz offers solid international coverage with strong European and Asian networks. If you're not American and won't regularly access US healthcare, paying Aetna's premium for US integration you won't use doesn't make sense.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Choose Aetna International</strong> if you're American or need regular US healthcare access. The CVS integration, large US network, and seamless experience for US visits justify the price. If you're choosing between "Allianz with US add-on" vs "Aetna with US included," Aetna is usually the better value.
  </p>

  <p>
    For corporate assignees, check your employer's offerings—corporate Aetna plans are often competitively priced and may be the best option regardless of your individual preference.
